Good — clean run. Here's a full post-deployment verification sweep. Set your context once, then work down.

```bash
NS=dev-epay-common        # adjust if your workloads land in a different namespace
REL=epay-common
ISTIO_NS=dev-istio-system
```

## 1. Helm release health — confirm the upgrade is recorded as deployed

```bash
helm status $REL -n $NS
helm history $REL -n $NS | tail -5
```
Look for `STATUS: deployed` on the latest revision. The revision number should have incremented from the last run.

## 2. Everything the release rendered — is any object unhealthy?

```bash
# All resources this release owns, across the namespace
oc get all -n $NS

# Anything not Running / not Ready anywhere in the namespace
oc get pods -n $NS -o wide | grep -Ev '([0-9]+)/\1 .*Running|Completed' || echo "all pods healthy"
```

## 3. Pods — restarts, crashloops, pending

```bash
oc get pods -n $NS --sort-by=.status.startTime

# Flag any with restarts or bad phase
oc get pods -n $NS -o json | jq -r '
  .items[] | select(
    (.status.containerStatuses // [] | map(.restartCount) | add // 0) > 0
    or (.status.phase != "Running" and .status.phase != "Succeeded")
  ) | "\(.metadata.name)  phase=\(.status.phase)  restarts=\([.status.containerStatuses[]?.restartCount] | add)"'
```
Empty output = nothing restarting or stuck.

## 4. Recent events — the fastest way to spot silent failures

```bash
oc get events -n $NS --sort-by=.lastTimestamp | tail -30 | grep -Ei 'warn|error|fail|back-off|unhealthy' || echo "no warning events"
```

## 5. The Kiali CR that was failing — confirm it reconciled cleanly

Since epay_common installs cluster tooling, verify Kiali specifically (that was your last blocker):

```bash
# CR accepted and status
oc get kiali -A
oc get kiali kiali -n $ISTIO_NS -o jsonpath='{.status.conditions}{"\n"}' 2>/dev/null \
  || oc get kiali -n $ISTIO_NS -o wide

# query_timeout landed as integer 30 (the field that was rejected)
oc get kiali kiali -n $ISTIO_NS -o jsonpath='{.spec.external_services.tracing.query_timeout}{"\n"}'
# expect: 30

# Kiali pod up
oc get pods -n $ISTIO_NS -l app=kiali -o wide
```

## 6. The CRB you adopted — confirm Helm still owns it

```bash
oc get clusterrolebinding dev-kiali-cluster-monitoring-view \
  -o jsonpath='managed-by={.metadata.labels.app\.kubernetes\.io/managed-by}{" release="}{.metadata.annotations.meta\.helm\.sh/release-name}{"\n"}'
# expect: managed-by=Helm release=epay-common
```

## 7. Confirm your changes actually reflected (not a no-op deploy)

This is the "did my edit take effect" check. Compare what Helm has stored against the live cluster:

```bash
# What Helm believes it deployed (the rendered manifests for this revision)
helm get manifest $REL -n $NS | grep -A2 query_timeout

# The values Helm actually used
helm get values $REL -n $NS | grep -i query_timeout
```
Both should show `30`, proving your values fix is what's live — not a cached older revision.

## 8. Other cluster tooling epay_common installs — Tempo, monitoring, network policies

Your chart deploys more than Kiali. Sweep the pieces:

```bash
# Tempo / OpenTelemetry / monitoring objects the chart created
oc get tempo,tempostack -A 2>/dev/null
oc get servicemonitor,prometheusrule -n $NS 2>/dev/null
oc get networkpolicy -n $NS
oc get secret -n $NS | grep -Ei 'tempo|kiali|eiscert' 

# The sibling cluster-scoped bindings — confirm none are orphaned/erroring
for crb in dev-kiali-dev-istio-system-oauth dev-kiali; do
  oc get clusterrolebinding "$crb" \
    -o jsonpath="$crb managed-by={.metadata.labels.app\.kubernetes\.io/managed-by}{\"\n\"}" 2>/dev/null \
    || echo "$crb absent"
done
```

## 9. One-shot rollup

If you want a single pass/fail glance:

```bash
echo "== Helm ==";        helm status $REL -n $NS | grep -E 'STATUS|REVISION'
echo "== Bad pods ==";    oc get pods -n $NS --no-headers | grep -Ev '([0-9]+)/\1 .*Running|Completed' || echo "  none"
echo "== Warn events =="; oc get events -n $NS --field-selector type=Warning --sort-by=.lastTimestamp | tail -5 || echo "  none"
echo "== Kiali ==";       oc get kiali kiali -n $ISTIO_NS -o jsonpath='  timeout={.spec.external_services.tracing.query_timeout}{"\n"}'
```

## Interpreting results

Green = `STATUS: deployed`, no pods outside `Running/Completed`, no Warning events, Kiali CR shows `query_timeout: 30` and its pod is up, and the CRB still reads `managed-by=Helm`.

If something's off, the two most likely spots given this chart:
- A pod stuck `ContainerCreating` → usually a secret/configmap mount (you've hit the `/certs` shadowing issue before — check `oc describe pod <name> -n $NS` events).
- Kiali pod `CrashLoopBackOff` despite CR accepted → check `oc logs -n $ISTIO_NS -l app=kiali`, often the empty `url:`/`provider:` tracing fields if the CRD coerced them oddly.

